## .NET Performance Analysis — `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`

**Context:** Hot-path code processing millions of log entries/minute.

### Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.IndexOf(string)` no `StringComparison` | 0 |
| `.Substring(` | 0 |
| `.StartsWith`/`.EndsWith` no `StringComparison` | 0 |
| `.ToLower()`/`.ToUpper()` | 0 |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()` | 1 |
| Chained `.Replace(` | 0 |
| `params` keyword | 1 (code) + 1 (comment) |
| `.Select(`/`.Where(`/`.Take(`/`.Any(`/`.Aggregate(` | 15 call sites |
| `.ToList()`/`.ToArray()` | 4 |
| `new List<` (non-static) | 1 |
| `static readonly Dictionary<` / `FrozenDictionary<` | 0 / 0 |
| `new Regex(` / `RegexOptions.Compiled` / `GeneratedRegex` | 0 / 0 / 0 |
| Unsealed non-static classes | 1 of 1 (0 sealed) |

### Positive Findings

- ✅ `new List<string?>(8)` at L91 — pre-sized capacity for known max elements
- ✅ No `string.Format` boxing — uses string interpolation throughout
- ✅ No regex, no async, no `Substring` allocations
- ✅ No `HttpClient` or serialization anti-patterns

---

### Findings

#### 1. LINQ Chains on Hot Path (15 instances)
🔴 **Critical**

**Impact:** Each `Humanize()` call produces ~5–8 enumerator allocations, ~3–4 delegate allocations, and ~2–3 intermediate collections. At millions of calls/minute this creates tens of millions of short-lived Gen0 objects per minute.

**Files:**
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128` — `.Any(x => x != null)`
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L140,L143,L146,L149` — `.Where().Take().Where()` + `[.. timeParts]` materialization
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L158,L169` — `.Where().ToList()` + `.Take()`
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L244,L261-262` — `.Select()` and double `.Select().Select()`
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L270-272,L284` — `.Select().Where().ToArray()` + `.Take()`
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L304` — `.Aggregate()`

**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops and manual list building. For example:

`IsContainingOnlyNullValue` (L127–128):
```csharp
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

`SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` (L133–150):
```csharp
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int count = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (count >= precision) break;
        if (!countEmptyUnits && part == null) continue;
        if (countEmptyUnits) count++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            result.Add(part);
            if (!countEmptyUnits) count++;
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

`HumanizeDisplayStrings` (L266–286) — replace `.Select().Where().ToArray()` + `.Take()`:
```csharp
private string HumanizeDisplayStrings(IEnumerable<string?> strings, string separator)
{
    var items = new List<string>();
    foreach (var item in strings)
    {
        if (item == null) continue;
        var trimmed = item.AsSpan().Trim();
        if (trimmed.IsEmpty) continue;
        items.Add(trimmed.ToString());
    }
    // ... rest of method
}
```

---

#### 2. `enum.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` Compound Allocation (1 site, called per time unit)
🟡 **Moderate**

**Impact:** 2 string allocations per non-zero time unit (enum `ToString()` + `ToLowerInvariant()`). With precision=3, up to 6 unnecessary allocations per `Humanize()` call.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`

**Fix:** Pre-compute a static lookup array indexed by `(int)TimeUnit`:
```csharp
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
    Enum.GetValues<TimeUnit>().Select(u => u.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()).ToArray();

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = s_unitNames[(int)unit];
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

---

#### 3. `params IStringTransformer[]` Array Allocation (1 instance)
🟡 **Moderate**

**Impact:** Allocates a `T[]` on every `Transform()` call. Common case (1 transformer) pays for an array it doesn't need.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L303`

**Fix:** Add a 1-arg overload for the common case:
```csharp
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);
```
On .NET 9+/C# 13, change to `params ReadOnlySpan<IStringTransformer>` for zero-alloc at all arities.

---

#### 4. Unsealed `DefaultCollectionFormatter` (1 of 1 non-static classes)
ℹ️ **Info**

**Impact:** Prevents JIT devirtualization of the 4 `virtual Humanize` methods. Each virtual call through the interface has higher dispatch cost than a sealed class.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L208`

**Fix:** Add `sealed` keyword: `public sealed class DefaultCollectionFormatter`

**Caveat:** Only if this class is not subclassed elsewhere. If it is designed for inheritance, leave unsealed.

---

### Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| 🔴 Critical | 1 | 15 LINQ call sites on hot path — ~10+ allocations per `Humanize()` call |
| 🟡 Moderate | 2 | `enum.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` compound alloc; `params` array alloc |
| ℹ️ Info | 1 | Unsealed class prevents devirtualization |

The dominant issue is **Finding 1** — the pervasive LINQ usage. For a logging framework at millions/minute, replacing the LINQ chains with `foreach` loops would eliminate the majority of per-call GC pressure in this code.

> ⚠️ **Disclaimer:** These results are generated by an AI assistant and are non-deterministic. Findings may include false positives, miss real issues, or suggest changes that are incorrect for your specific context. Always verify recommendations with benchmarks and human review before applying changes to production code.
